## 2. ZERO-TYPE TRANSFORMATIONS ($\mathcal{Z}$)

Zero-Type transformations are symmetry operators that stabilize cognitive states by normalizing them around what "zero" means in that domain.

| Zero Type | Operator | Mathematical Definition | Purpose |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Additive Zero** | $T_{+}$ | $T_{+}(S) = S - \mu$ | Remove cognitive bias ($\mu$). |
| **Multiplicative Zero** | $T_{\times}$ | $T_{\times}(S) = S/\|S\|$ | Normalize magnitude, preserve direction. |
| **Complex Zero** | $T_{i}$ | $T_{i}(S) = S \cdot i$ | Orthogonalization; reframe the situation. |
| **Quaternion Zero** | $T_{q}$ | $T_{q}(S) = q S q^{-1}$ | Rotate worldview without altering structure. |
| **Topological Zero** | $T_{\text{top}}$ | $S \simeq S'$ (under homotopy) | Allow deformation without identity loss. |
| **Information Zero** | $T_{KL}$ | $D_{KL}(P \parallel Q) = 0$ | Match distributions, align interpretations. |

The full set of stabilization operators is $\mathcal{Z} = \{ T_+, T_{\times}, T_i, T_q, T_{\text{top}}, T_{KL} \}$.

